Assignment 1 challenges us to use CIMpgr to diagram the processes that our mock company will implement.

{:#sec1}
{:start="1"}
1. PROCESS MODEL: Develop your own company’s modular, object-oriented quality project / system model/ process model in ISO standard CIMpgr. Your model basically should explain how your company processes work. You remember in Assignment 0 you set up a company, now here you explain your project-management focus operations, processes, activities, data flows, etc. SImple as that! ... Use the process model templates in the eBook with your content and designs too; don't copy-paste only.... read the web article specified below). Visio 2003 version is compatible with the templates, and is available FREE from NJIT (as a free download for students), or for some days free from Microsoft over the web. Obviously you can use any other good 2D drawing tool too. (I use the best, OmniGraffle, but it works only on the Mac; sorry no MS version is available.)

The primary process for GreenSpeed is order fulfillment and distribution.  For us, this will be a sequential process where the customer provides their requirements at a high level, and we help them analyze them in order to establish a project charter.  This will ensure that all of the expectations, assumptions, and estimates are laid out in writing before any resource allocation or implementation gets started.  Following acceptance of the project charter, our buyers take point on sourcing any products or services needed to fulfill the charter.  Once allocations and internal purchasing is complete, the parallel processes of distribution and service/repairs/training can begin.  Some charters will only need one or the other, but we anticipate that new customer onboarding will almost always engage both of these processes.  Each process's deliverable is fed back to prior processes in the sequence to establish an interative feedback loop, facilitating continuous improvement.

IS

A1.2 IS

\* The resource allocation process based on a Project Charter.

```
allocations = [];
FOR EACH resource IN charter
    DO determine best timeframe given resource availability and project plan
    AND allocations.push(new Allocation(resource, timeframe));
END FOR
RETURN new AllocationReport(allocations);
```

---

A1.3 IS

\* Assign the order details based on the Resource Allocations Report

```
service_orders = [];
purchase_orders = [];

FOR EACH service_resource_allocation IN allocation_report
    DO service_orders.push(new ServiceOrder(service_resource_allocation))
END FOR

FOR EACH purchasing_allocation IN allocation_report
    DO purchase_orders.push(new PurchaseOrder(purchasing_allocation))
END FOR

RETURN (service_orders, purchase_orders) //tuple represents parallel deliverables
```

7. PANORAMA NAVIGATION MAP: In the eBook please find the panoramic navigation map of a small USA town with 360 degree panoramas (very cool new technology I have created and programmed with my brother). Find this panorama set in the eBook, review it and explain how you could use this technology for understanding civil and construction engineering, and other project management processes, for modeling processes, and for improving processes. Write about 250 words on this after having reviewed the panoramic navigation objects, as well as the related links with more pictures, videos and other objects. Please do not ask me to find it for you in the eBook; IF you read it, you'll find it... Also, you'll find some gyro-enabled 360 degree panorama links in the eBook. These also relate closely to civil and construction engineering management / any other project management. Please review these too and write about any 2 of them as above. 

The panorama featured in the eBook is a great tool to use whenever spatial information needs to be quickly conveyed to visual learners.  A 360-degree panorama can either be cylindrical or spherical.  Both types can pan left and right, but spherical panoramas can also tilt up and down.  The panoramas featured in the eBook are spherical, but cylindrical ones are easier to program in terms of user experience, so if there is nothing to be gained by visualizing the vertical access, that programming time can be better spent elsewhere.

If professional photography equipment is available, then a circular fisheye lens can be paired with a panoramic head to very quickly capture two opposing still images.  Each image captured with a circular fisheye has a 180 degree field-of-view in both vertical and horizontal axes, so only two images are needed to capture a full sphere of information, as long as the camera can be perfectly levelled to the horizon, and the two images are captured with exactly 180 degrees of rotation between them.  Stereoscopic images can also be used if true-to-life 3D, or virtual reality compatibility is desired.

If such equipment is not available, then a camera with a gyroscopic sensor and a narrower field-of-view lens can be used.  All modern smartphones fit this criteria, and the fact that all standard smartphone cameras contain the ability to shoot partial cylindrical panoramas belies this fact.  There are apps available for both iOS and Android which enable the capture of 360-degree cylindrical and spherical panoramas.  These apps operate by capturing overlapping images at the phone’s standard field of view, cross referencing the captured images with data from the phone’s internal gyroscope, and stitching the images together in the proper sequence given the relative orientation of the phone in space when said image was captured.  In most cases, the results are indistinguishable, but the smartphone method does introduce significantly higher potential for artifacts due to objects in the scene being captured moving around between shots.

With respect to civil and construction engineering, such panoramic experiences can be used to help all stakeholders visualize the project at all stages.  A simulated rendering of the completed project can be projected onto a panorama to give a sense of scale and allow the viewer to experience the final product at his/her own pace rather than being forced into the pace of a traditional video walkthrough.  This rendering can be decomposed to show the project in various stages of completion, and can also be employed for quality control to identify defects quickly.  Textual information can be overlayed in a heads-up display as in the eBook’s example, or as interactive elements like on <http://redondo.supraluminal.io>. (This is a prototype interactive shopping experience developed by a family member of mine - source code is available at <https://github.com/nvaldes/redondo.js>.  The white dots are interactive points.  Pan 90 degrees to the right and click on the scarf or bathrobe to see the overlay concept in action.)  The technology is flexible enough to support whatever experience the engineering team needs to fit the purpose.

Continually improving and introducing innovation to our company while maintaining a TQM focus will be the key to success. CIMpgr process flow diagrams and method is primordial for the monitoring and continuous improvement of the process, it also helps understand the deliverables and variables in a process to help attain results and meet deadlines. The diagraming and documentation of the process using CIMpgr allows for a more throughout modeling where various layers of a process can be displayed, in a parent-to-child format. It also makes the information more accessible and includes all the quality reviews and feedback in the modeling. The processes then can be analyzed one by one to innovate and better perform. Using CIMpgr alongside with other visual aids like panoramic views of the processes, the staff of this company will have available clearer information to take decisions and explore solutions that bring us closer to a perfect and balance TQM.

**[Cummins invests in GE Additive metal binder jetting technology as company reveals new generation beta machine]({{ site.baseurl }}{% link _posts/2019-07-02-assignment-1-social-networking-article-1.md %})**

I was the dissenting voice in this discussion.  Where my classmates expressed excitement at the prospect of a 100-year-old manufacturing firm embracing 3D printing, I remained skeptical due to the method.  Binder jetting relies on sintering after the print is completed to actually join the powder particles together, and the joint is not as strong as other methods where the metal fully melts.  Unless Cummins is only using this for prototyping or proof-of-concept, I would worry that the production use of sintered parts would negatively impact the durability of their engines, which are currently renowned for their performance.

**[Essentium details quest to enable additive manufacturing at scale at AMUG 2019]({{ site.baseurl }}{% link _posts/2019-07-02-assignment-1-social-networking-article-3.md %})**

I really like Essentium.  They approach 3D printing with the exact attitude that I was complaining about above.  Rather than be content with just using it for PR's sake, they are expanding the technology so that it can actually scale to production speed.  This is the kind of research that 3D printing sorely needs, because the upstart costs for it are huge.  Being able to use the same machines for both prototyping an production is a massive benefit to smaller companies that can't afford two different loadouts.  Essentium's focus on trust is also unique.  Most of the companies investing in 3D printing are focused on agility or novelty or cost-cutting, but these guys are putting their focus where it counts.
